column2: This file is a key to go from the montly bin type weather cities specified in HOT2XP/2000 to available houly CWEC weather city data files.
IT IS RECOMMENDED TO USE AT LEAST THE LONGITUDE FROM CWEC, OTHERWISE THE AMBIENT TEMPERATURE AND SOLAR INSOLATION ARE OUT OF PHASE
There are many HOT2XP/2000 weather city names because those programs only require monthly binned weather data.

column3: HOT2XP selectable weather city name for a dwelling.
HOT2XP province abbreviation. These were entered by Lukas Swan.
HOT2XP province name for weather location.
HOT2XP latitude for weather location determined from Environment Canada website. These were entered by Lukas Swan.
HOT2XP longitude for weather location determined from Environment Canada website. These were entered by Lukas Swan.
HOT2XP heating degree days below 18 degrees C for weather location determined from Environment Canada website. These were entered by Lukas Swan.
HOT2XP cooling degree days above 24 degrees C for weather location determined from Environment Canada website. These were entered by Lukas Swan.

column2: The following are shallow ground (estimate 3 m depth) temperature information from BASECALC program distributed by NRCan. They are used for the NN and possibly to fill out BASESIMP. The values were discovered in the file citiese.dat distributed with the BASECALC package.

column3: The BASECALC city used for this weather city. The values were cross referenced to CWEC or HOT2XP city names, for missing names the most representative (i.e. HDD and nearby) city was chosen by LS.
The annual average ground temperature (depth of 3 m?)
The amplitude which the ground temperature changes from the average throughout the year. For use with the Moore model
The phase lag of the temperature rise (see Moore model or BASESIMP description)

column2: CWEC stands for Canadian Weather for Energy Calculations. It is based on many different years weather data and is designed to be representative of the climate.

column3: CWEC filename for all Canadian climates from the extras/climate folder of the ESP-r subversion respository.
CWEC weather city name provided in the ascii CWEC data. These were grammatically corrected by Lukas Swan.
CWEC province name abbreviation provided in the ascii CWEC data. These were entered or corrected by Lukas Swan.
CWEC province full name. These were entered by Lukas Swan.
CWEC weather year provided in the ascii CWEC data. As CWEC is representative from many years, the year value is considered arbitrary.
CWEC latitude provided in the ascii CWEC data.
CWEC longitude difference from nearest meridian, provided in the ascii CWEC data. Negative is West and positive is East of the meridian.
CWEC radiation flag provided in the ascii CWEC data. Its use is unknown?
CWEC latitude from data obtained for similarly names locations on the Environment Canada Website for Canadian Climate Normals. These were entered by Lukas Swan.
CWEC longitude from data obtained for similarly names locations on the Environment Canada Website for Canadian Climate Normals. These were entered by Lukas Swan.
CWEC heating degree days based on 18 degrees C from data obtained for similarly names locations on the Environment Canada Website for Canadian Climate Normals. These were entered by Lukas Swan.
CWEC cooling degree days based on 24 degrees C from data obtained for similarly names locations on the Environment Canada Website for Canadian Climate Normals. These were entered by Lukas Swan.

column2: The following are the difference between the HOT2XP site and the CWEC site for weather comparison

column3: Difference between the HOT2XP latitude value and the most representiative CWEC site
Difference between the HOT2XP longitude value and the most representiative CWEC site
Difference between the HOT2XP HDD value and the most representiative CWEC site
Difference between the HOT2XP CDD value and the most representiative CWEC site
The ratio of HOT2XP HDD site value to the most representative CWEC site
